oping to find a polity to which he could belong, Șăineanu moved with his family to Paris in 1900 and became Lazare Sainéan. There he made innovative studies of French popular speech and slang, culminating in his great work on the origins of that language. Once again, he was contributing to the development of a national tongue. Even then, while welcomed by literary scholars, Sainéan was unable to get a permanent university post. Though a naturalized citizen of France, he felt himself a foreigner, an “intruder,” into his old age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aPhilologistszFrancevBiography. 0aPhilologistszRomaniavBiography. 0aPhilologyxPolitical aspects. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  aLaz?r Schein.  aMoses Gaster.  aZionist movement.  aanti-Semitism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633865941?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865941/original  a978-3-11-078048-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK